The source code at line 4 is:
```
int fib(int n) {
  return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);
}
```

The program has a recursive function fib that calls itself with no base case, leading to unbounded recursion and eventually a stack overflow.



The response from GDB is:
```
n = 100
```

We can see that the function fib is being called with a value of 100, which is a large number.



The source code at line 9 is:
```
auto const n = 100;
```

The variable n is being set to a large value of 100, which causes the recursive function fib to overflow the stack.

[ROOT CAUSE:] The root cause of this crash is that the recursive function fib has no base case and is being called with a large value of n, causing a stack overflow.

[LOCAL FIX:] A minimal local fix would be to add a base case to the recursive function fib to prevent it from overflowing the stack. We can add a condition to check if n is less than 2 and return 1 in that case.

```diff
--- program.cpp.orig
+++ program.cpp
@@ -4,7 +4,7 @@
 int fib(int n) {
-  return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);
+  if (n < 2) {
+    return 1;
+  }
   return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);
 }
```

[GLOBAL FIX:] A more thorough root-cause fix would be to redesign the function fib to use an iterative approach instead of recursion. This would prevent the function from overflowing the stack and make it more efficient.

